fr:mainmatter.fr:p:
Let \mathbb {C} and \mathbb {D} be two categories. An adjunction between
\mathbb {C} and \mathbb {D} consists of functors F :  \mathbb {C}   \to   \mathbb {D} and
U :  \mathbb {D}   \to   \mathbb {C} equipped with a natural transformation
\eta  :  \mathbf {1} _{ \mathbb {C} }  \to  U  \circ  F such that


    for any C  \in   \mathbb {C} , D  \in   \mathbb {D} and any \mathbb {C}-morphism f : C  \to  U(D),
    there exists a \mathbb {D}-morphism g : F(C)  \to  D unique with the property
    of making the following diagram commute:

       \usepackage {tikz-cd}

       \begin {tikzcd}
        U(F(C))  \arrow [r, "U(g)"] & U(D) \\ 
        C  \arrow [u, " \eta _C"]  \arrow [ur, "f"]
       \end {tikzcd}
